2
00:00:15,515 --> 00:00:18,435
<i>and see how letters exist
in the environment.</i>

3
00:00:20,061 --> 00:00:21,396
<i>I think, as a typeface designer,</i>

4
00:00:21,479 --> 00:00:23,773
<i>you can't help but look
at the typography of everything.</i>

5
00:00:25,900 --> 00:00:28,528
<i>One of the really fun things
about typeface design</i>

6
00:00:28,611 --> 00:00:30,739
<i>is nothing is out of bounds.</i>

7
00:00:31,239 --> 00:00:33,783
<i>You can love rare manuscripts.</i>

8
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:39,080
<i>You can love graffiti. You can love logos
done by Madison Avenue design agencies.</i>

9
00:00:40,123 --> 00:00:43,668
<i>Everything you've ever read
has been shaped by hand.</i>

10
00:00:44,627 --> 00:00:47,922
<i>It's a profound thought
that every single letter you consume,</i>

11
00:00:48,006 --> 00:00:50,633
<i>that there is somewhere a person,
or a team of people,</i>

12
00:00:50,717 --> 00:00:51,968
<i>who have drawn this thing</i>

13
00:00:52,052 --> 00:00:54,179
<i>and released it into the world.</i>

14
00:00:55,055 --> 00:00:57,307
<i>We reach a point where everybody
has a favorite typeface.</i>

15
00:00:57,390 --> 00:01:01,061
<i>The fact that you can choose the font
on your phone or your computer</i>

16
00:01:01,144 --> 00:01:04,189
<i>has really sensitized everyone
to what typography can do.</i>

17
00:01:05,106 --> 00:01:08,443
<i>We're making raw materials
that are open to interpretation.</i>

18
00:01:08,526 --> 00:01:11,780
<i>That's really what it is
that moves visual culture forward. </i>

19
00:01:28,213 --> 00:01:30,298
[woman] <i>Jonathan was this wunderkind.</i>

20
00:01:30,381 --> 00:01:33,259
<i>You know, he had such an amazing way
