26
00:01:50,235 --> 00:01:51,986
<i>He is the best of the best. </i>

27
00:01:57,784 --> 00:01:59,202
[Jonathan] Typography is a dialogue

28
00:01:59,285 --> 00:02:01,871
between typeface designers
who create alphabets

29
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:03,873
and graphic designers who use them.

30
00:02:03,957 --> 00:02:05,458
And it's a two-way street.

31
00:02:05,917 --> 00:02:09,504
The Public Theater behind us
has an identity designed by Paula Scher,

32
00:02:09,671 --> 00:02:11,339
who was in season one of <i>Abstract.</i>

33
00:02:11,422 --> 00:02:14,509
I grew up at a time
when Paula's work was everywhere.

34
00:02:14,592 --> 00:02:17,095
And I grew up, therefore,
with a sense that wood type

35
00:02:17,178 --> 00:02:19,097
was part of the fabric of typography.

36
00:02:19,597 --> 00:02:21,683
In the early '90s, I began

37
00:02:21,808 --> 00:02:24,394
creating a typeface family of my own
called Knockout.

38
00:02:24,561 --> 00:02:27,564
It's meant to be inspired
by these kinds of wood types.

39
00:02:27,897 --> 00:02:29,899
So, it was really kind of a delight that

40
00:02:29,983 --> 00:02:32,443
Paula, when she designed the identity
for the Public Theater,

41
00:02:32,527 --> 00:02:34,154
used Knockout for the design.

42
00:02:34,404 --> 00:02:37,240
So, it's really this
sort of wonderful synergy of...

43
00:02:37,699 --> 00:02:39,784
being inspired by graphic designers,

44
00:02:40,118 --> 00:02:42,495
creating typefaces
that get used by graphic designers,

45
00:02:42,871 --> 00:02:45,123
and seeing the way they do things
that are unexpected.

46
00:02:46,082 --> 00:02:48,001
<i>Typefaces are a raw material. </i>

47
00:02:48,209 --> 00:02:50,461
<i>To be a typeface designer is like</i>

48
00:02:50,545 --> 00:02:53,047
<i>being the designer of a color of paint.</i>

49
00:02:53,381 --> 00:02:55,925
<i>We're not painting houses,
we're not decorating houses,</i>

50
00:02:56,009 --> 00:02:57,385
<i>we're supplying the color. </i>

51
00:02:59,929 --> 00:03:01,639
<i>♪ These are letters ♪</i>

52
00:03:05,560 --> 00:03:07,353
<i>Typeface design is sleight of hand.</i>

53
00:03:07,604 --> 00:03:11,482
<i>Even a simple goal, like make all
the letters the same size, isn't easy.</i>

54
00:03:11,733 --> 00:03:14,485
<i>To make the letters C and T
appear the same height,</i>

55
00:03:14,569 --> 00:03:17,363
<i>the C has to be drawn
so that it's actually taller.</i>

56
00:03:17,739 --> 00:03:19,282
<i>Round letters exceed flat ones</i>

57
00:03:19,365 --> 00:03:21,951
<i>by an amount the type designer
has called overshoot.</i>

58
00:03:25,163 --> 00:03:27,123
<i>Another goal of typeface design
is balance.</i>

59
00:03:27,624 --> 00:03:31,044
<i>To make a letter like B feel as if its top
and bottom halves match,</i>

60
00:03:31,127 --> 00:03:32,795
<i>they often need to be drawn differently.</i>

61
00:03:33,421 --> 00:03:36,716
<i>Turn it over, and you'll see that
it's actually smaller above than below.</i>

62
00:03:38,676 --> 00:03:42,138
<i>The humble letter T conceals
one of the alphabet's great paradoxes.</i>

63
00:03:42,430 --> 00:03:45,350
<i>To make vertical and horizontal strokes
look equally thick,</i>

64
00:03:45,516 --> 00:03:48,603
<i>the verticals are drawn much thicker
than the horizontals.</i>

65
00:03:48,686 --> 00:03:52,440
<i>This is called anisotropic contrast,
and it affects all the letters,</i>

66
00:03:52,523 --> 00:03:55,151
<i>none more so than the diabolical letter S.</i>

67
00:03:55,652 --> 00:03:58,988
<i>An S that's balanced and centered
looks bizarre when turned around.</i>

68
00:03:59,072 --> 00:04:01,157
<i>It's thinner at the top and bottom,</i>

69
00:04:01,449 --> 00:04:03,993
<i>thicker in the middle,
and it leans slightly backwards.</i>

70
00:04:16,089 --> 00:04:19,634
<i>Typeface design is a slow process.
It can take decades, sometimes.</i>

71
00:04:19,717 --> 00:04:23,012
<i>There is no obvious route
from beginning to end,</i>

72
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:25,807
<i>and there's no guarantee
of getting to the end, either.</i>

73
00:04:27,141 --> 00:04:28,768
<i>About ten years ago,</i>

74
00:04:28,935 --> 00:04:31,479
<i>I had an idea that I'd buy a wristwatch.</i>

75
00:04:32,272 --> 00:04:34,607
<i>As I began really looking critically
